events.name: Practicing Coding Interviews
events.description:
Ready to find a new software development job? Just want to keep your skills sharp, or learn a new way of solving problems? We'll focus on writing code as well as finding conceptual solutions. We have copies of the book. All you need to bring is pencil and paper or a laptop.

Please sign in and get a nametag at the front desk, then come join us on the 2nd floor, on the opposite side of the building from the elevators. We'll set up to meet from 6:30-8:30pm, with a hard stop at 8:45pm. It’s OK to arrive late or leave early. If you find yourself locked out of the building after 7pm, contact the meetup host in the #pci channel on the PuPPy Slack team (go to slack.pspython.com to join PuPPy Slack channel).

We ask that attendees show up no earlier than 30 minutes prior to the beginning of the meetup (i.e. no earlier than 6:00 p.m.) to allow Galvanize time to fully prepare for our event.

events.name: At Textio for 1st time, 2nd Wednesday of the Month Talk Format Meeting
events.description:
Seeking beverage sponsor for the event

• What we'll do
Two Talks scheduled -- will have third

by George Reilly

- Jon Peck
Developer Advocate & Software Engineer at Algorithmia

Jon loves sharing tech stories and jamming with novice devs and CTOs alike about the world of Serverless & Machine Learning. He's Seattle-based, but frequently travels to SFO, PDX, and misc tech conferences.

- George Reilly
Most recently Principal Engineer Metabrite, George is currently job searching

George is an experienced developer with 20+ years of professional experience. Architecture, design, implementation, testing, debugging, and operations. He has co-written two programming books. He is a Tech-Ed speaker and longtime Toastmaster.

George over his career has done a lot, from web apps to hypervisors, typography and text editors, terminal emulators and TV shows, performance and usability, 3D graphics and assembly language, high-end servers and 8-bit microcomputers, HTTP kernel driver to CSS debugging — though not all at the same time.

Specialties: Web services, Python, Linux, Win32, .NET, server software, DevOps, web servers, web clients, performance, C++, C#, JavaScript, HTTP, ASP.NET, testing, Classic ASP, IIS, graphics, GUIs.

• What to bring
Yourself

• Important to know
Textio providing food; Currently seeking a beverage sponsor

events.name: Hack Night @ WeWork Denny Triangle
events.description:
Welcome to Seattle JS Hack Night at the new WeWork Denny Triangle!

Come join your fellow JavaScripters and learn and hack together!

What is a Hack Night?
Seattle JS Hack Nights are open and inclusive after hours hacking events for turning big ideas into JavaScript-powered realities. It's the perfect way to meet passionate JavaScripters and to ignite and amplify personal productivity and collaboration.

We organize coding sessions at venues in Seattle each week. Our sessions encourage peer ideation, knowledge sharing, new champions for causes and projects, and a heightened sense of community.

If you have a cool project, work on it with us!

What if I'm a novice?
We have a wide range of experience levels, and some of us love to teach (because you usually learn something when you teach, right?) So don't be afraid. Come on over.

Want to keep in touch?
Join the Seattle JS Hackers Slack Group! (

>https://seattlejshackers.slack.com/shared_invite/MTcxMTI1NDM5NjU1LTE0OTI0Nzg3MzktNzA4ZTM5OTQ3Yg)

*** Having trouble getting in? Text 765-444-9253 or 808-223-3899 ***

events.name: Sunday Coffee Break
events.description:
A biweekly coding session at a great location. There's not really an agenda, just bring a laptop and something to work on! We have developers of many skill levels at the event, so don't feel intimidated if you are brand new. Many of us love to help out newbies. Nick will be there from 12-5 so feel free to show up and leave at your convenience.

For those who are driving in, Parking can be difficult, I tend to park a few blocks away on the street since street parking is free on Sundays.

I hope to see you there!
events.how_to_find_us: Nick will make a post on the event saying where we are at, Seating varies week to week.

events.name: Summer BBQ Series #1 - Gas Works Park
events.description:
/>

This is the first BBQ of our 2018 Summer BBQ Series. We will have one BBQ event each month at a different location from May to September:

Here is a little history of Gas Works Park:

This 20 acre point on Lake Union was cleared in 1906 to construct a plant to manufacture gas from coal - later converted to crude oil. Import of natural gas in the 1950's made the plant obsolete. The city acquired the site and the park was opened to the public in 1975. The boiler house has been converted to a picnic shelter with tables, fire grills and an open area. The former exhauster-compressor building, now a children's play barn, features a maze of brightly painted machinery.

Friends, family and pets are welcome!

Cost of the BBQ is $10 per person.

BBQ starts at 12noon and we will be there at 11:30am to set up stuff, it is much appreciated if you could come early and give us a hand.

We have reserved tables #1 and 2 in the BBQ area next to the boiler house and there will be signs saying that the tables and grills are reserved for Meetup event.

When you arrive please check in with the event hosts.

There will be vegetarian options!!!

*A few other Meetup groups are also invited to this event*

events.description:
This Korean study group is for people who want to learn Korean. Usually, our native Korean teacher teaches from 2:00 to 4:00 and the students talk and help each other from 4:00 to 5:00. It's free and for people of any level!!

The room changes every week depending on which room is available, check this meetup page before coming. Leave a message on this page if you need directions.

events.name: 치맥하고 노래방 (chicken, beer and karaoke)

group.name: Washington Korean Language and Culture Exchange

events.description:
This date may change, I want to see how many people want to go.

The max is 24 but I can change it if more people want to come.

There’s only two large rooms and those rooms can hold 12 people comfortably.
If more people want to show up then that is fine but they will have to be in a separate smaller room. The karaoke is in the room and I can also serve you beer and chicken everything you want while you’re singing in the room. And if you come and you’re under 21, we can do one room that is non-drinking and the other room with drinks. They are extremely strict on this so be warned

I will offer to give people rides if you come to the U district. Only four people can fit in my car. I’m sure there’s other people who would give a ride to others as well.
